John Edward: Languages skills essential for world citizens
The independent schools in Scotland have an excellent record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another series of excellent exam results, as well as individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community initiatives.
With more than 30,000 students in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their pupils for secondary and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a custom-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain popular and desirable subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: ‘If you talk to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
When you talk to him in his own language, you reach his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English alone when we want to build relationships and a bond of trust with people from other countries.
From the recent exam results of this year, we can conclude that languages are at the top of the ranking, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of the students who studied foreign languages achieved a high score.
The data, collected from 74 schools joined SCIS, show that 72 percent of the students scored a high score (‘A’) in Mandarin, while 72 percent of the students received an A, 69 percent of the students in French and 63 percent of the students in Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now valued as much as STEM subjects (science, technology, technology and mathematics) in independent school programmes and elsewhere.
A 2014 study of the UK Employment and Skills Commission showed that 17% of the obstacles to filling in job vacancies were attributed to a lack of language skills, according to employers.
Language skills thus become increasingly important to prepare young people for their future future.
As more and more jobs require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Whatever career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future with such a skill for life.
Communicating directly with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person the advantage of competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation. French was the only language that exceeded 10%, with a total of 15%.
This is why investing in language education is now important for today's children.
Several languages, especially those of emerging economies, will provide children with a better chance of finding a meaningful job.
In Scotland, schools choose which languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important to the United Kingdom when they look ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interest of your child, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers specializing in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed, regardless of the future.
It cannot at present be denied that languages in a global business environment remain vital to the country's future, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be regarded as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
Il fat bee le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
