National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
New research carried out on a estate in the Scottish highlands is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
It is hoped that the findings will shed light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and contribute to future conservation activities.
The study carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland follows the ordinary and the small dwarf bat, the brown large-eared bat and the water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at key locations around the estate to track the activities of bats throughout the season.
NTS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile investigations using hand detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bat's screams and what kind of thing to do.
A map of the habitat and a report is then produced to make a detailed picture on the landscape scale of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, NTS Nature Conservation Advisor, hopes that the results show which habitat areas are the most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of pastures and how we can best maintain the forests for bats and similar species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have decreased significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities affecting sleeping places and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightnings can also pose a risk, as can fly-catchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are actually not blind.
Their night hunting habits, however, make their ears more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use an advanced echo location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight route.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts, who regularly investigate, inspect sleeping places and sometimes perform rescue actions.
The organization has even set up the first and only reserve for bats in Scotland at the estate Threeave in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of the ten species of bats of Scotland live.
Landscape manager David Thompson says the estate is the ideal territory for bats.
"Here in Threeave we have a great environment for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But so much is not yet known about bats, and that's why the work we're doing here and at other locations will help us better understand what they need in order to thrive."
It emphasises the importance of monitoring bats before maintenance work is carried out, as the possible unconscious destruction of a dormitory can lead to the death of 400 female bats and their young, possibly eliminating a full local population.
Bats are a protected species of animals and it is illegal to kill, trouble or disrupt them or to destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer for the Bat Conservation Trust, asked the public to make a contribution to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and many of our species, we just don't know how their populations are."
